'''Autocunnilingus''' is [[cunnilingus]] performed by a woman on herself, by sucking or using her tongue on her own [[genitalia]] as a form of [[masturbation]].<ref>"autocunnilingus", ''The Complete Dictionary of Sexology'', expanded ed., ed. Robert T. Francoeur ''et al''., New York: Continuum, 1995, {{ISBN|9780826406729}}, p. 49.</ref>
== Documentation == An unusually high degree of flexibility such as that of a [[contortionist]] would be required to perform the act.<ref>"Schlangenfrau gesucht" - "Sought: snake-woman", Mario Günther-Bruns, ''Sexgott: 1.000 Tabubrüche'', Diana 60223, Munich: Heyne, 2013, {{ISBN|9783453602236}}, [https://books.google.com/books?id=K-i2CuvUwNMC&pg=PT10 n. p.] {{de icon}}</ref><ref>Eva Christina, ''The Book of Kink: Sex Beyond the Missionary'', New York: Perigee, 2011, {{ISBN|978-0-399-53694-6}}, {{OCLC|706018293}}, [https://books.google.com/books?id=SFcWmcGLXJ4C&pg=PT52 n. p.]</ref><ref>Jesse Bering, "So Close, and Yet So Far Away: The Contorted History of Autofellatio", in ''Why Is the Penis Shaped Like That?: And Other Reflections on Being Human'', New York: [[Scientific American]] / Farrar, Straus, Giroux, 2012, {{ISBN|9780374532925}}, pp. 11&ndash;16, [https://books.google.com/books?id=BO2j5b2hs8IC&pg=PA291 p. 16].</ref><ref>Drawing, ''Art of Love: Nearly 100 Sex Positions and Wealth of Illustrated Material from Foreplay to Anatomy'', e-book, Mobilereference.com, 2007, {{ISBN|9781605011172}}, [https://books.google.com/books?id=Q384wPT-KFEC&pg=PT1 n.p.]</ref> Unlike the male equivalent, [[autofellatio]], which requires a less extreme [[frontbend]] and is known to be achievable by a small fraction of the male population,<ref>William Guy and Michael H. P. Finn, "A Review of Autofellatio: A Psychological Study of Two New Cases", ''[[Psychoanalytic Review]]'' 41 (1954) 354&ndash;58.</ref> autocunnilingus has not been reliably documented as achievable. {{As of|2015|01}}, [[PubMed]], the medical literature database maintained by the [[US National Library of Medicine]], which contains several descriptions of autofellatio, contained no mentions of autocunnilingus.<ref>[https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=autocunnilingus Search for "autocunnilingus"], [[PubMed]], US National Library of Medicine / National Institutes of Health, January 7, 2015.</ref> Autocunnilingus was also not found in a study of sexual humour based on transformation of [[proverb]]s.<ref>Anna T. Litovkina, "Sexuality in Anglo-American Anti-Proverbs", in ''The Pragmatics of Humour across Discourse Domains'', ed. Marta Dynel-Buczkowska, Pragmatics & Beyond, new series 210, Amsterdam / Philadelphia: Benjamins, 2011, pp. 191&ndash;214, {{ISBN|9789027256140}}, [https://books.google.com/books?id=xbVxAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA205 note 10, p. 205].</ref> It has, however, been reported as a self-destructive fantasy,<ref>''Fear of Being Fat: The Treatment of Anorexia Nervosa and Bulimia'', ed. C. Philip Wilson with Charles C. Hogan and Ira L. Mintz, Classical psychoanalysis and its applications, New York: Aronson, 1983, {{ISBN|9780876684801}}, [https://books.google.com/books?id=Z3ZHAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA145 p. 145].</ref> and occurrences have been reported in non-human primates.<ref>[[David Linden|David J. Linden]], ''The Compass of Pleasure: How Our Brains Make Fatty Foods, Orgasm, Exercise, Marijuana, Generosity, Vodka, Learning, and Gambling Feel so Good'', New York: Viking-Penguin, 2011, {{ISBN|9780670022588}}, [https://books.google.com/books?id=42GY_PXexMMC&pg=PT103 n.p.]: the example that follows involves water from a garden hose rather than the mouth.</ref>
=== Fiction === In "Besorgung", one of his ''Venetian Epigrams'', [[Goethe]] imagined Bettina becoming sufficiently limber to perform autocunnilingus and do without men.<ref>Ludger Lütkehaus, "'O Wollust, o Hölle': Onanie, Phantasie und Literatur", ''[[Die Zeit]]'', 15 November 1991, [http://www.zeit.de/1991/47/o-wollust-o-hoelle/seite-10 p. 10] {{de icon}}</ref><ref>W. Daniel Wilson, ''Goethe Männer Knaben: Ansichten zur "Homosexualität"'', Berlin: Insel, 2012, {{ISBN|9783458175421}}, p. 500 (pdf [http://www.onleihe.de/static/content/suhrkamp/20120815/978-3-458-79321-2/v978-3-458-79321-2.pdf p. 8]) {{de icon}}</ref> [[Camille Paglia]] compares the resulting image to [[William Blake]]'s "engravings of solipsistically contorted figures".<ref>[[Camille Paglia]], ''[[Sexual Personae: Art and Decadence from Nefertiti to Emily Dickinson]]'', 1990, repr. New York: Vintage, 1991, {{ISBN|9780679735793}}, [https://books.google.com/books?id=fhuC6eHWnqQC&pg=PA252 p. 253].</ref>
