'''The northern riverine forest''' is a type of forest ecology most dominant along waterways in the northeastern and north-central [[United States]] and bordering areas of [[Canada]]. Key species include [[willow]], [[elm]], [[American sycamore]], [[Trillium undulatum|painted trillium]], [[Coptis|goldthread]], [[Common wood sorrel|common wood-sorrel]], [[Cypripedium acaule|pink lady's-slipper]], [[Aralia nudicaulis|wild sarsaparilla]], and [[Populus deltoides|cottonwood]].<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=http://www.maine.gov/dacf/parks/publications_maps/AWWBroc/AWW13.html|title=FORESTS AND FLOWERS|last=|first=|date=|website=Maine.gov|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref>

One of the distinct ecosystems is the Riverine Forest. These are found on the lower flood plains along the rivers edge. The main species found here is one of the deciduous species; the [[Populus balsamifera|Balsam Poplar]]. These trees like a high volume of moisture and are able to tolerate flooding. They are distinguishable by their thick, gnarly bark and their larger, pointed leaves. These leaves have a distinct drip tip. The trees supply homes for the many native species of fauna. 

Other Key trees include [[Betula alleghaniensis|yellow birch]], [[Betula papyrifera|white birch]], [[Acer saccharum|sugar maple]], [[Fagus grandifolia|American beech]], [[Tsuga canadensis|eastern hemlock]], [[white pine]], [[Pinus resinosa|red pine]], [[Quercus rubra|northern red oak]], [[Prunus pensylvanica|pin cherry]], and [[Picea rubens|red spruce]].<ref name=":0" />

Key shrubs include [[Acer pensylvanicum|striped maple]] and [[Viburnum lantanoides|hobblebush]].<ref name=":0" />

